1515":"1475–1515","1473":"1473","1484":"1484","1594":"1594","1472":"1472","29 Aug 1594":"29 augustus 1594","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","18 Feb 1559":"18 februari 1559","1559":"1559","Bicton, Devon, England":"Bicton, Devon, England","Holcombe, Devon, England":"Holcombe, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Holcombe Burnell, Bicton, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Holcombe Burnell, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1510–29 Aug 1594":"1510–29 August 1594","1510–1594":"1510–1594","1484–Female":"1484–Deceased","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1472–1559":"1472–1559","1475–1515":"1475–1515","1473":"1473","1484":"1484","1594":"1594","1472":"1472","29 Aug 1594":"29 August 1594","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","18 Feb 1559":"18 February 1559","1559":"1559","Bicton, Devon, England":"Bicton, Devon, England","Holcombe, Devon, England":"Holcombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Holcombe Burnell, Bicton, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Holcombe Burnell, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dennis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Denis(e)</i>, <i>Dinis(e)</i>, vernacular forms of Latin <i>Dionysius</i>, Greek <i>Dionysios</i> ‘(follower) of <i>Dionysos</i>’, an eastern god introduced to the classical pantheon at a relatively late date and bearing a name of probably Semitic origin. The name was borne by various early Christian saints, including Saint Denis, the martyred 3rd-century bishop of Paris who became the patron saint of France. From the 12th century onward, the popularity of the name in England (and of its cognates, mainly   Denis  , in the continental Europe) seems to have been largely due to French influence. The feminine form <i>Dionysia</i> (in vernacular English likewise <i>Den(n)is</i>) is also found, and some examples of the surname may originate from it.","English: from Middle English <i>deneis</i>, a variant of <i>danais</i> ‘Danish’, with the vowel influenced by Middle English <i>denshe</i> (Old English <i>denisc</i>). Compare   Dence  .","Irish (mainly Dublin and Cork): of the same origin as 1 and 2 above, sometimes an alternative form to   Donohue   but more often to   McDonough  , since the personal name <i>Donnchadh</i> was Anglicized as <i>Donough</i> or <i>Denis</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Dec","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Aleksander, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignacy, Jerzy, Krystyna, Krzysztof, Malgorzata, Mikolaj, Stanislaw, Tadeusz.","Polish: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Dionizy</i>, Polish form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Dennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Tennyson  .","English (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>deinzein</i>, a burgess who enjoyed the privileges of those living <i>deinz la cité</i> ‘within the city’."]},{"name":"Denny","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>Den(n)y</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Tenney  .","English: habitational name from Danny in Hurstpierpoint, Sussex, recorded as <i>Danye</i> in 1343. Alternatively, the name may arise from Denny in Waterbeach, Cambridgeshire, but no medieval evidence with a habitative preposition has been found in the case of the latter.","Scottish: habitational name from Denny in Stirlingshire."]},{"name":"Diniz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Augusto, Celso, Francisco, Luis, Ricardo, Rogerio, Alvaro, Anselmo, Antero, Carlos.  Portuguese Joao, Marcio.","Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Dinis</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Denes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Bela, Laszlo, Miklos, Tibor, Aranka, Balint, Endre, Ferenc, Lajos, Zoltan.  Jewish Imrich, Meyer.  Romanian Doina, Matei, Radu.","Hungarian (<b>Dénes</b>): from the personal name <i>Dénes</i>, from Greek <i>Dionysios</i> (see   Dennis  ). The surname <i>Dénes</i> is also found in Slovakia; compare 2 below.","Slovak (<b>Deneš</b> and <b>Déneš</b>) and Romanian (also <b>Deneş</b>): from the Hungarian personal name <i>Dénes</i> ‘Dennis’, or an adaptation of the Hungarian surname <b>Dénes</b> (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Dennett","meanings":["English: from a pet form of Middle English <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ), or possibly from a pet form of <i>Denise</i>, as, for example, <i>Denote</i>, a female character in <i>Piers Plowman</i>."]},{"name":"Dinges","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dings  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Dings","meanings":["Dutch and German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dinges  ."]},{"name":"Dinis","meanings":["Portuguese and Galician: from <i>Dinis</i>, a Portuguese personal name equivalent to   Dennis  ."]}]},{"name":"Michaell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Michael ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mikayla","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Michaela ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":75,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":77,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Michaell Dennis was born in 1510, in Bicton, Devon, England, his father, Sir William Thomas Dennis , Lord of Holcombe, was 38 and his mother, Lady Jane Loveday 14thGG, was 35. He died on 29 August 1594, in Devon, England, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1510–29 Aug 1594":"1510–29. august 1594","1510–1594":"1510–1594","1484–Female":"1484–Surnud","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1472–1559":"1472–1559","1475–1515":"1475–1515","1473":"1473","1484":"1484","1594":"1594","1472":"1472","29 Aug 1594":"29. august 1594","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","18 Feb 1559":"18. veebruar 1559","1559":"1559","Bicton, Devon, England":"Bicton, Devon, England","Holcombe, Devon, England":"Holcombe, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingstone, Kent, England":"Kingston, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Holcombe Burnell, Bicton, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Holcombe Burnell, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1510–29 Aug 1594":"1510–29. elokuuta 1594","1510–1594":"1510–1594","1484–Female":"1484–Kuollut","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1472–1559":"1472–1559","1475–1515":"1475–1515","1473":"1473","1484":"1484","1594":"1594","1472":"1472","29 Aug 1594":"29. elokuuta 1594","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","18 Feb 1559":"18. helmikuuta 1559","1559":"1559","Bicton, Devon, England":"Bicton, Devon, England","Hol